LAST UPDATES

LMU und TUM open Konrad Zuse School

On July 26th the Grand Opening of the Konrad Zuse School of Excellence took place in Munich. The vision of the ‘Konrad Zuse School of Excellence in Reliable AI’ (relAI) is to train future generations of AI experts, who for the first time combine technical brilliance with awareness of the importance of AI’s reliability. The school is embedded in the unique transdisciplinary Munich AI ecosystem, combining the expertise of the two Universities of Excellence TUM and LMU and closely integrates various non-university research institutions and industry partners.

Read more here

Artificial Neurons Based on Semiconductor Technology

The NEHO project, led by Dr. Andreas Tittl, an Emmy Noether group leader at the Chair of Hybrid Nanosystems of the Nanoinstitute Munich, is conducting ongoing research on ultrafast neural networks based on semiconductor technology. The project aims to develop energy-efficient alternatives to current AI and machine learning technologies by combining materials science and photonics. By utilizing hybrid electron-photon quasiparticles called plasmons, the researchers seek to control photon flow on small scales, potentially leading to faster and more efficient information processing.

Read more here

Structures in the Fog

AI tools such as the Stable Diffusion model developed by Prof. Dr. Björn Ommer  are teaching computers how to see and paint. LMU's EINSICHTEN magazine  published a portrait about Prof. Ommer about the impact of AI-generated art, its implications for human creativity, copyright challenges. Prof. Dr. Björn Ommer has the Chair of AI for Computer Vision and Digital Humanities / the Arts and he also heads the Computer Vision & Learning Group (CompVis).

Read more here

Prof. Dr. Jürgen Schmidhuber at MCML

On July 14, the Munich Center for Machine Learning (MCML) hosted Prof. Dr. Jürgen Schmidhuber at LMU as part of the Munich AI Lectures. He is one of the best-known researchers in the field of Artificial Intelligence. In his lecture he shared thoughts on AI, the origins of Deep Learning, Generative Adversarial Networks and LSTM networks gave the audience insights into the genesis of modern AI systems.

Read more here

Data Science for Social Good Fellowship

The Data Science for Social Good (DSSG) Fellowship starts today and gives aspiring young data scientists a chance to tackle real-world social problems. For 2 months nine students will be working on solving real-world problems. DSSG is an initiative founded at the University of Chicago in 2013 to enhance the use of data science and AI for social good. Hosted by Prof. Dr. Frauke Kreuter and Prof. Dr. Bernd Bischl at the Department of Statistics and the MCML, the DSSG fellowship program is now brought to Munich.

Read more here
UPCOMING EVENT

AI-Talk with Prof. Dr. Yann LeCun

On 29. September 2023 Prof. Dr. Yann LeCun will give an AI-Talk at LMU. The talk will be part of the Center for Advanced Studies (CAS) research focus Next Generation AI and titled "From Machine Learning to Autonomous Intelligence". Prof. Dr. Yann LeCun is Chief AI Scientist for Meta AI Research and Silver Professor at the Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences at New York University.
